<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Basic Mechanics of Double-Moving<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.91)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9916'>Norman "Asterisk" Harrison</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9916&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 18, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Sting and Glamdring. 2 strikingly similar weapons with the common ground of being able to see an opponent&#39;s hand and removing twilight for orcs. Glamdring&#39;s damage+1 for Gandalf, Sting&#39;s extra strength for Frodo to stop an overwhelm. Simple enough weapons, and yet in my opinion, 2 of the strongest cards in the game, and some of the most powerful tools to help you move twice, a vital part of winning the race in Lord of the Rings.<br>
<br>
When you move twice, you sweat your opponent. Putting pressure on your opponent helps sway control of the game towards you and puts your opponent in a position to lose the game. Moving twice needlessly or heedlessly gives your opponent a chance to deal damage and put you down, winning the game. Obviously, making sure that your moves always benefit you more than your opponent is vital to winning the race and thus the game; remember, even if you plan to beat your opponent with your shadow your fellowship should still be able to win, or at the very least, keep the pressure on your opponent. This article should help to delve into the important, albeit simplistic, aspects of moving a second time.<br>
<br>
When you play Sting or Glamdring, be prepared, your relation ship with your opponent is going to get a lot better real soon, cause they&#39;re not going to be keeping any more secrets from you. Get ready to slap em in their poker face, cause that bluff no longer has any power or influence. Don&#39;t be worried about giving up too much twilight against orcs, just remove with these, and remember, you can do it more than once. The extremely versatile applications of these cards, along with the handy power bonuses make these weapons some of your most powerful toold for moving again. PACK THIS HEAT!!!!!!!!!!!! I can&#39;t stress enough how this has helped me in my playing days, and i rarely have a deck that doesn&#39;t run at least 1 Sting. As strong as these cards are, however, they can&#39;y do the job alone.<br>
<br>
The fundamental problem with moving again is there is no preparation besides practice and training your mind: it&#39;s all metagame and it&#39;s all a judgement call. As a result, learning to weigh problems and hindrances, pros and cons and possible obstacles or results of the move is the only way to prepare. Above all, practice helps you get a feel for the deck and how far you can push a double move in general.<br>
<br>
Weighing your potential losses is an important part of being able to move again. If you see what damage you&#39;ll be taking, and how you can deal with it, you&#39;ll have a better chance of safely moving again. There are several factors that affect your losses and they all contribute directly to your decision. An oversimplified equation:<br>
<br>
If Loss > Necessity, don&#39;t do it. It&#39;s not worth it. Some of the major factors affecting the losses that might be suffered are:<br>
<br>
1. Twilight, Following Minions, and Sites.<br>
2. Possible Positive Effects for Your Opponent.<br>
<br>
The twilight you have left in the pool makes an obvious contribution to whether or not you will be moving again. More often than not, your opponent will not use all the pool you provide, and anything that&#39;s left will help them lay the beatdown next move. Each companion will also add twilight, barring some card such as No Stranger to the Shadows. Finally, the site you are moving to will add it&#39;s twilight to the total. A basic site list:<br>
<br>
3: 0 twilight<br>
4: Avg. 3 twilight<br>
5: 6 twilight<br>
6: 3 twilight<br>
7: 6 twilight<br>
8: Avg. 7.5 twilight<br>
9: Avg. 8.5 twilight<br>
<br>
Again, a simple equation will suffice here:<br>
<br>
Twilight left + # of companions + site avg. = amount of twilight for more cards and thus the damage your opponent can deal.<br>
<br>
Anticipate what will be thrown at you. If fighting Sauron Orcs, don&#39;t expect more than 1 minion/5 twilight until site 6. Uruk will have about 1 minion/3 twilight starting at Hollin. Moria can play about 1 minion/1 twilight, often times exceeding that using conditions and runners. Nazgul will play 1 minion/5 twilight, and put the greatest hurt on at sites 2 and 3.<br>
<br>
Following minions also add to the double move decision. Any and all minions surviving the regroup phase will be dealt with again by the fellowship. Again, simple, if you think the following minions will do serious damage, hols off on that move.<br>
<br>
Lastly, the site also contribute quite a bit to your second move. Barring the use of a regroup event or the event that you are much behind your opponent, your second move will be to an opponent&#39;s site. Generally, an opponent&#39;s site is included to do the maximum amount of damage to you, so their influence should be considered. It is easiest to memorize the especially harmful sites and what deck archetypes they are used with, but it&#39;s not essential. A basic knowledge of the sites or a simple generic amount of damage can be attributed to the site addition when calculating whether or not to move. Just saw a Nazgul? Better not double move to three with a big pool, cause it&#39;s the Ford of Brunien. Just moved to seven, leaving an opponent with orcs at 5 or 6? Might wanna try that double move and make sure they can&#39;t come from behind and stop you at the Shores of Nen Hithoel. <br>
<br>
Pretty simple so far, huh? Well it gets just a bit more complex.<br>
<br>
While double-moving seems most opportune for you, it&#39;s potential to help your opponent is nearly as great. Often times, an opponent&#39;s hand will be clogged with minions, leaving their fellowship weak and unsupported. Moving a second time gives them a chance to dump their shadow and set up a free peoples hand without worrying. A single move will force them to hold some in order to offer resistance in case you try to move again. Not only does it give them a chance to needlessly dump minions, it gives them an extra discard, which is incredibly powerful. being able to ditch 2 cards of your choice to set up your hand can almost clinch a double move. Also, it may help them cycle free peoples and shadow cards throughout their decks. Ideally, if a player has 8 cards in hand, 4 are free peoples and 4 are shadow. again, ideally, when you move they will play their 4 shadow and redraw; odds say they will draw 2 free peoples and 2 shadow. Moving again gives them a chance to drop those other 2 shadow, potentially setting up their free peoples hand with 7 cards that are usable, allowing them to recycle and get more shadow, only to drop them on your turn. Stopping this can be done with strategic single moves to hurt your opponent, and Sting and Glamdring pop up again here. if during the Shadow phase your opponent has 6 or 7 shadow cards in hand, try not to move, whether or not you can weather the storm. This forces them to hold mot of these until next turn, as they can&#39;t drop them on their own turn. This creates an &quot;awkward&quot; throughput of free peoples and shadow cards, and giving them the wrong cards at the wrong time, which can be just as helpful as moving again. Furthermore, a free peoples player with shadow cards in hand is not likely to be able to double-move against a decent shadow, forcing them to stop at or behind your site and allowing you to be able to save your double-move for when you&#39;re going to a sanctuary or where you will suffer minimal losses.<br>
<br>
There are good results to move twice, and motivations are nearly as numerous as hindrances. the importances of setting pace for your opponent and putting pressure on them, as well as the regroup phase and your current hand will contribute as positive effects to moving again.<br>
<br>
It&#39;s a race. Chances are, if you wanna win, you wanna win the race. Plain and simple, double-moving puts you ahead. Setting a pace for your opponent helps to apply pressure on them to catch up with you or forget trying to win with their free peoples, causing them to make risky or normally dangerous decisions in order to stay in the game, putting you in a position to kill them and win. However, running ahead when you&#39;ve got a 2 site lead is unnecessary. Wait until they start trying to catch up to run again. If they&#39;re not in danger, you&#39;re not in danger, just maintain a lead.<br>
<br>
The regroup phase and your hand often times contribute to your move. Effects that end during the regroup phase, such as taking off the ring or savagery to match their numbers wearing off can have an impact on the gameplay. Actions performed during the regroup phase are often the most powerful in the game, like exerting a ranger to discard a minion or wound all minions. Actions like these can pave the way for your second move. Lastly, if your hand is still tocked with free peoples cards after the first move, good job. You have successfully planned ahead and prepared yourself for another move. You will be able to drop all your free peoples cards without worry of retribution and will be able to provide a shadow threat and stop you opponent. While the Balrog is dangerous, he tends to get a lot more timid when you&#39;ve got Gandalf with Glamdring and 3 Servant of the Secret Fire in your hand. Worried about the Cave Troll? Don&#39;t be, if you&#39;ve got plenty of archery exertions to make and/or Valiant Man of the West or some stealth cards. Finally, don&#39;t let your own strategy backfire on you. Don&#39;t let your hand stay clogged with free peoples card during your opponent&#39;s turn, use your second move to dump extraneous free peoples cards.<br>
<br>
So, by this time, either you&#39;re just about ready to give me a 5 for changing the way you think about double-moving, or a 2 because this presented you with no new real information. If you&#39;re in the former, apparently, i have done my job. I have helped a fellow gamer with a strategy that they will apply in playing. If you&#39;re in the latter, you are as good a player/a better player than me, and I have just wasted your time. I apologize. I hope I have put some aspects of the game in perspective and made words out of the unconscious actions of most gamers.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading.<br>
*****<br>
